Think through this step by step before answering. Your reasoning must follow
these four steps, in order:
1. Read the claim: restate what the claim asserts in your own words.
2. Find the evidence: identify the specific evidence in the source relevant
   to the claim.
3. Compare: explicitly compare the claim against the evidence — where do
   they agree, where do they diverge?
4. Select the verdict: choose the verdict label that matches your
   comparison, using the definitions below.

VERDICT DEFINITIONS — use these exact definitions:

SUPPORTED: the claim accurately represents what the source says. Numbers, methods,
and conclusions match the source. Paraphrasing is acceptable — judge factual accuracy,
not wording. EXCLUSION: Do NOT upgrade a claim to SUPPORTED if it requires inferential
leaps or assumptions not explicitly written in the chunk text.

PARTIALLY_SUPPORTED: one part of the claim is backed by the source, but another part
is either absent from the source or factually incorrect. For example: the method is
correct but the reported number is wrong, or the main conclusion is supported but an
additional claim layered on top is not in the source.

NOT_SUPPORTED: the specific assertions in the claim — numbers, methods, outcomes, or
conclusions — are either directly contradicted by the source or do not appear in it at
all. A wrong number is always NOT_SUPPORTED, never PARTIALLY_SUPPORTED — a factual
error is not a partial truth. Do not use PARTIALLY_SUPPORTED as a fallback when the
core assertion is absent or incorrect. When a claim combines factual background (which
may be in the source) with a specific factual assertion (which is not), the specific
assertion is the core — if it is absent, the verdict is NOT_SUPPORTED, not
PARTIALLY_SUPPORTED. EXCLUSION: Do NOT downgrade a claim to NEEDS_HUMAN_REVIEW simply
because the language style differs — focus entirely on semantic facts.

INSUFFICIENT_EVIDENCE: the retrieved chunks do not contain enough information to make
a judgment. Use only when retrieval clearly failed or returned off-topic content — not
as a fallback for difficult cases.

NEEDS_HUMAN_REVIEW: the evidence is genuinely ambiguous or contradictory and a human
expert is needed to make the final call.

EXAMPLES:

SUPPORTED — Example 1:
  Claim: "Goodfellow et al. (2014) proposed training two competing
  neural networks to generate realistic data samples."
  Source says: "We simultaneously train two models: a generative
  model G and a discriminative model D."
  Verdict: SUPPORTED — the claim accurately paraphrases the source.
  The core assertion (two competing networks for generation) matches.

SUPPORTED — Example 2:
  Claim: "Vaswani et al. (2017) introduced the Transformer
  architecture, which relies entirely on attention mechanisms."
  Source says: "We propose a new network architecture, the
  Transformer, based solely on attention mechanisms."
  Verdict: SUPPORTED — paraphrasing of the same factual content.
  No numbers, methods, or conclusions differ from the source.

PARTIALLY_SUPPORTED — Example 1:
  Claim: "The authors found that the intervention improved patient
  outcomes in elderly populations, but had no effect on younger
  patients."
  Source says: "The intervention improved patient outcomes in elderly
  populations."
  Verdict: PARTIALLY_SUPPORTED — the first part of the claim matches
  the source, but the second part ("no effect on younger patients")
  does not appear in the source at all.

PARTIALLY_SUPPORTED — Example 2:
  Claim: "The authors found that sleep deprivation impairs working
  memory performance, and concluded that this effect is primarily
  driven by disruption to hippocampal consolidation."
  Source says: "Sleep deprivation significantly impaired working
  memory across all three measures."
  Verdict: PARTIALLY_SUPPORTED — the impairment finding is in the
  source, but the mechanistic explanation (hippocampal consolidation)
  is not stated or implied in the retrieved evidence. One part of the
  claim matches; the added interpretive layer does not.

PARTIALLY_SUPPORTED — Example 3 (near-miss contrast with SUPPORTED):
  The two sub-examples below use the same source sentence. Notice
  how a small addition to the claim changes the verdict.

  Sub-example A — PARTIALLY_SUPPORTED:
    Claim: "Vaswani et al. (2017) introduced the Transformer, which
    relies entirely on attention mechanisms, making it the first
    architecture to achieve human-level performance on translation."
    Source says: "We propose the Transformer, based solely on
    attention mechanisms, and achieve state-of-the-art results on
    two machine translation tasks."
    Verdict: PARTIALLY_SUPPORTED — the attention-only architecture
    is confirmed by the source; "human-level performance" is not
    stated anywhere in the source and is an addition beyond what the
    paper claims.

  Sub-example B — SUPPORTED (same source, tighter claim):
    Claim: "Vaswani et al. (2017) introduced the Transformer, relying
    entirely on attention mechanisms, and achieved state-of-the-art
    results on machine translation tasks."
    Source says: same sentence as above.
    Verdict: SUPPORTED — this paraphrase matches the source exactly.
    No assertion is added beyond what the source states.

NOT_SUPPORTED — Example 1:
  Claim: "The model achieved 94% accuracy on the benchmark dataset."
  Source says: "Our model reached 89% accuracy on the test set."
  Verdict: NOT_SUPPORTED — the specific number in the claim (94%)
  differs from the source (89%). A wrong number is a factual error,
  not a paraphrase. Do not use PARTIALLY_SUPPORTED for wrong numbers.

NOT_SUPPORTED — Example 2:
  Claim: "Zhai (2022) found that students using ChatGPT completed
  tasks 40% faster than students who did not use AI."
  Source says: "The writing process took 2-3 hours and involved very
  limited professional knowledge from the author."
  Verdict: NOT_SUPPORTED — the claim describes a controlled student
  comparison that does not exist in the source. The core assertion
  is entirely absent from the retrieved evidence.

INSUFFICIENT_EVIDENCE — Example 1:
  Claim: "The proposed algorithm reduces training time by half
  compared to the baseline."
  Retrieved chunk: "Table 3 shows the results of our experiments."
  Verdict: INSUFFICIENT_EVIDENCE — the retrieved chunk references
  a table but contains no actual data. The content needed to verify
  the claim was not retrieved.

INSUFFICIENT_EVIDENCE — Example 2:
  Claim: "Berg (2023) argues that AI tools improve research
  efficiency."
  Retrieved chunk: "References: [1] Smith et al. [2] Jones et al."
  Verdict: INSUFFICIENT_EVIDENCE — the retriever returned a
  references section with no substantive content. Retrieval
  clearly failed for this case.

NEEDS_HUMAN_REVIEW — Example 1:
  Claim: "Johnson & Lee (2019) demonstrated that neural networks
  outperform humans on all medical imaging tasks."
  Source: No paper by Johnson & Lee (2019) on this topic can be
  found. The DOI does not resolve and no matching title or authors
  appear in the literature.
  Verdict: NEEDS_HUMAN_REVIEW — the citation cannot be verified
  and requires expert judgment.

NEEDS_HUMAN_REVIEW — Example 2:
  Claim: "Martinez et al. (2021) proposed a new loss function that
  eliminates overfitting entirely in deep neural networks."
  Source: The DOI resolves to a paper on a completely unrelated
  topic (climate modelling) by different authors.
  Verdict: NEEDS_HUMAN_REVIEW — the source and claim are
  mismatched in a way that requires human review to resolve.

